<p>
  annual multi-trip travel insurance is sold as a convenience: one policy, all your trips, sorted. the reality is more complicated. for most uk travellers, it's a recurring cost that auto-renews at a quietly increased price — and is almost never the right policy for their actual travel patterns.
</p>

<h3>the usage gap</h3>

<p>
  the average uk annual travel insurance policy costs £45–80/year. but the average brit takes 2.4 overseas trips per year. if those are short european breaks, single-trip policies would cost £8–15 each — a total of £20–35. annual policy holders are overpaying by roughly £25–45/year for coverage they don't fully use.
</p>

<p>
  the gap is wider for families. a family annual policy costs £80–150. but two european holidays with single-trip family policies costs £40–60. the annual policy premium is double what you need.
</p>

<h3>the auto-renewal trigger</h3>

<p>
  annual travel insurance almost always auto-renews. and because the renewal email often arrives months after your last trip, it's easy to ignore. the direct debit hits, and you've paid for another year of coverage you might not use.
</p>

<p>
  perch. recommendation: cancel annual travel insurance after your last trip of the year. buy single-trip policies for each holiday instead. if you genuinely take 4+ trips a year, the annual policy might make sense — but compare the total cost of single trips vs the annual premium before auto-renewing.
</p>
